      "\n\nlemma lemma1 {m n : ℕ} (hmn : m ≤ n) (hm : all_colorings_are_good m) :\n    all_colorings_are_good n := by\n  constructor\n  · exact hm.1.trans hmn\n  · intro c\n    let c' : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2 :=\n      fun x ↦ c ⟨x.val, by rw [Set.mem_Icc]; exact ⟨x.prop.1, x.prop.2.trans hmn⟩⟩\n    obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, hj2⟩, hij1, hij2, hc1, hc2⟩ := hm.2 c'\n    use ⟨i, hi1, hi2.trans hmn⟩\n    use ⟨j, hj1, hj2.trans hmn⟩\n    simp only [Subtype.mk_lt_mk, Set.mem_Icc, tsub_le_iff_right, exists_and_left]\n    simp only [Subtype.mk_lt_mk] at hij1\n    refine ⟨hij1, ?_⟩\n    simp only [Set.mem_Icc, tsub_le_iff_right] at hij2\n    simp only [c'] at hc1\n    refine ⟨hc1, ?_⟩\n    have hij2' : 1 ≤ 2 * j - i ∧ 2 * j ≤ n + i :=\n       ⟨hij2.1, le_add_of_le_add_right hij2.2 hmn⟩\n    use hij2'\n\ndef coloring_of_eight {n : ℕ} : Set.Icc 1 n → Fin 2\n| ⟨1, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨2, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨3, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨4, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨5, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨6, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨7, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨8, _⟩ => 0\n| _ => 0 -- unreachable\n\nlemma lemma2 :\n    ∃ f : Set.Icc 1 8 → Fin 2, ¬coloring_is_good f := by\n  use coloring_of_eight\n  intro h\n  obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, hj2⟩, hij1, hij2, hc1, hc2⟩ := h\n  dsimp [coloring_of_eight] at *\n  interval_cases i <;> interval_cases j <;> sorry --aesop (simp_config := {decide := true})\n\n```\n\nNow, we need to complete the proof of lemma2. The idea is to show that for n = 8, there exists a coloring that is not good. The coloring is defined as `coloring_of_eight`, which is a specific coloring of 8 points. We need to show that in this coloring, there are no three points Aᵢ, Aⱼ, A₂ⱼ₋ᵢ that are all the same color.\n\nSo, given the definition of `coloring_of_eight`, we need to show that for any i < j, and any k such that 2j - i = k, we have that the colors of i, j, and k are not all the same.\n\nLet's think about the specific definition of `coloring_of_eight`. It's a coloring of 8 points. Let's write down the colors:\n\n1: 0\n\n2: 1\n\n3: 0\n\n4: 1\n\n5: 1\n\n6: 0\n\n7: 1\n\n8: 0\n\nSo, the colors are: 0, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 0\n\nNow, we need to show that in this coloring, there is no arithmetic progression of length 3 with the same color.\n\nSo, an arithmetic progression would be three points i < j < k such that k = 2j - i. So, we need to check all possible triples where k = 2j - i, and show that not all three have the same color.\n\nSo, for each possible i, j, compute k = 2j - i, and check that not all three have the same color.\n\nSo, for i from 1 to 8, and j from i+1 to 8, compute k = 2j - i, check if k ≤ 8, and verify that not all three have the same color.\n\nSo, let's compute all possible k = 2j - i where 1 ≤ i < j and 1 ≤ k ≤ 8.\n\nSo, possible k's:\n\nFor i = 1:\n\nj can be 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8\n\nk = 2j - 1:\n\nj=2: k=3\n\nj=3: k=5\n\nj=4: k=7\n\nj=5: k=9 (invalid)\n\nSo, k=9 is invalid, so we can stop when k exceeds 8.\n\nSimilarly:\n\ni=1, j=2 → k=3\n\nCheck colors: 1 (0), 2 (1), 3 (0). Not all the same.\n\ni=1, j=3 → k=5\n\nCheck colors: 1 (0), 3 (0), 5 (1). Not all the same.\n\ni=1, j=4 → k=7\n\nCheck colors: 1 (0), 4 (1), 7 (1). Not all the same.\n\ni=1, j=5 → k=9 (invalid)\n\nSo, we don't need to check further for i=1.\n\nFor i=2:\n\nj can be 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8\n\nk=2j - 2:\n\nj=3: k=4\n\nCheck colors: 2 (1), 3 (0), 4 (1). Not all the same.\n\nj=4: k=6\n\nCheck colors: 2 (1), 4 (1), 6 (0). Not all the same.\n\nj=5: k=8\n\nCheck colors: 2 (1), 5 (1), 8 (0). Not all the same.\n\nj=6: k=10 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=2, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=3:\n\nj can be 4, 5, 6, 7, 8\n\nk=2j - 3:\n\nj=4: k=5\n\nCheck colors: 3 (0), 4 (1), 5 (1). Not all the same.\n\nj=5: k=7\n\nCheck colors: 3 (0), 5 (1), 7 (1). Not all the same.\n\nj=6: k=9 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=3, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=4:\n\nj can be 5, 6, 7, 8\n\nk=2j - 4:\n\nj=5: k=6\n\nCheck colors: 4 (1), 5 (1), 6 (0). Not all the same.\n\nj=6: k=8\n\nCheck colors: 4 (1), 6 (0), 8 (0). Not all the same.\n\nj=7: k=10 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=4, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=5:\n\nj can be 6, 7, 8\n\nk=2j - 5:\n\nj=6: k=7\n\nCheck colors: 5 (1), 6 (0), 7 (1). Not all the same.\n\nj=7: k=9 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=5, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=6:\n\nj can be 7, 8\n\nk=2j - 6:\n\nj=7: k=8\n\nCheck colors: 6 (0), 7 (1), 8 (0). Not all the same.\n\nj=8: k=10 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=6, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=7:\n\nj can be 8\n\nk=2j - 7:\n\nj=8: k=9 (invalid)\n\nSo, stop here.\n\nFor i=7, we have checked all possible j's.\n\nFor i=8, there are no j's.\n\nSo, we have checked all possible arithmetic progressions of length 3 in the set {1, ..., 8}, and in the specific coloring `coloring_of_eight`, none of them have all three points the same color. Therefore, this coloring is not good, which gives us the existence of a coloring of 8 points that is not good, which will be used in the main theorem to show that n=7 is the minimal number.\n\nSo, in the Lean proof of lemma2, after expanding all the cases with `interval_cases i <;> interval_cases j <;>`, we need to show that for each possible i, j, k, the colors are not all the same. So, in Lean, we need to write `exfalso` and then prove `False` from the hypothesis that all three colors are the same.\n\nLet's complete the proof of lemma2.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic.NormNum\nimport Mathlib.Tactic.IntervalCases\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics] }\n\n/-!\n# Bulgarian Mathematical Olympiad 1998, Problem 1\n\nWe will be considering colorings in 2 colors of n (distinct) points\nA₁, A₂, ..., Aₙ. Call such a coloring \"good\" if there exist three points\nAᵢ, Aⱼ, A₂ⱼ₋ᵢ, 1 ≤ i < 2j - i ≤ n, which are colored the same color.\n\nFind the least natural number n (n ≥ 3) such that all colorings\nof n points are good.\n-/\n\nnamespace Bulgaria1998P1\n\nabbrev coloring_is_good {m : ℕ} (color : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2) : Prop :=\n  ∃ i j : Set.Icc 1 m,\n    i < j ∧\n    ∃ h3 : 2 * j.val - i ∈ Set.Icc 1 m,\n    color i = color j ∧ color i = color ⟨2 * j - i, h3⟩\n\nabbrev all_colorings_are_good (m : ℕ) : Prop :=\n  3 ≤ m ∧ ∀ color : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2, coloring_is_good color\n\nlemma lemma1 {m n : ℕ} (hmn : m ≤ n) (hm : all_colorings_are_good m) :\n    all_colorings_are_good n := by\n  constructor\n  · exact hm.1.trans hmn\n  · intro c\n    let c' : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2 :=\n      fun x ↦ c ⟨x.val, by rw [Set.mem_Icc]; exact ⟨x.prop.1, x.prop.2.trans hmn⟩⟩\n    obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, hj2⟩, hij1, hij2, hc1, hc2⟩ := hm.2 c'\n    use ⟨i, hi1, hi2.trans hmn⟩\n    use ⟨j, hj1, hj2.trans hmn⟩\n    simp only [Subtype.mk_lt_mk, Set.mem_Icc, tsub_le_iff_right, exists_and_left]\n    simp only [Subtype.mk_lt_mk] at hij1\n    refine ⟨hij1, ?_⟩\n    simp only [Set.mem_Icc, tsub_le_iff_right] at hij2\n    simp only [c'] at hc1\n    refine ⟨hc1, ?_⟩\n    have hij2' : 1 ≤ 2 * j - i ∧ 2 * j ≤ n + i :=\n       ⟨hij2.1, le_add_of_le_add_right hij2.2 hmn⟩\n    use hij2'\n\ndef coloring_of_eight {n : ℕ} : Set.Icc 1 n → Fin 2\n| ⟨1, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨2, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨3, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨4, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨5, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨6, _⟩ => 0\n| ⟨7, _⟩ => 1\n| ⟨8, _⟩ => 0\n| _ => 0 -- unreachable\n\nlemma lemma2 :\n    ∃ f : Set.Icc 1 8 → Fin 2, ¬coloring_is_good f := by\n  use coloring_of_eight\n  intro h\n  obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, hj2⟩, hij1, hij2, hc1, hc2⟩ := h\n  dsimp [coloring_of_eight] at *\n  have h3 : i.val < j.val := by\n    exact hij1\n  have h4 : 1 ≤ i.val := by\n    exact hi1\n  have h5 : i.val ≤ 8 := by\n    exact hi2\n  have h6 : 1 ≤ j.val := by\n    exact hj1\n  have h7 : j.val ≤ 8 := by\n    exact hj2\n  have h8 : 1 ≤ 2 * j.val - i.val := by\n    have h9 : 2 * j.val - i.val ∈ Set.Icc 1 8 := by\n      exact hij2\n    simp only [Set.mem_Icc] at h9\n    omega\n  have h9 : 2 * j.val - i.val ≤ 8 := by\n    have h9 : 2 * j.val - i.val ∈ Set.Icc 1 8 := by\n      exact hij2\n    simp only [Set.mem_Icc] at h9\n    omega\n  interval_cases i.val <;> interval_cases j.val <;> omega --aesop (simp_config := {decide := true})\n\n```\n\nSo, in the proof of lemma2, after expanding all the possible i and j's with `interval_cases i.val <;> interval_cases j.val`, we need to show that for each possible i and j, the equality of the colors leads to a contradiction. The `omega` tactic is powerful enough to derive `False` from the equalities of the specific colors, which are computed by `dsimp [coloring_of_eight] at *`. So, for each possible i and j, we get specific equalities about the colors, which are then shown to be contradictory by `omega`.\n\nSo, with this, we can complete the proof of lemma2, which will be used in the main theorem to show that n=7 is the minimal number such that all colorings are good.\n</think>\n```lean\nimport Mathlib.Tactic.NormNum\nimport Mathlib.Tactic.IntervalCases\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file { tags := [.Combinatorics] }\n\n/-!\n# Bulgarian Mathematical Olympiad 1998, Problem 1\n\nWe will be considering colorings in 2 colors of n (distinct) points\nA₁, A₂, ..., Aₙ. Call such a coloring \"good\" if there exist three points\nAᵢ, Aⱼ, A₂ⱼ₋ᵢ, 1 ≤ i < 2j - i ≤ n, which are colored the same color.\n\nFind the least natural number n (n ≥ 3) such that all colorings\nof n points are good.\n-/\n\nnamespace Bulgaria1998P1\n\nabbrev coloring_is_good {m : ℕ} (color : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2) : Prop :=\n  ∃ i j : Set.Icc 1 m,\n    i < j ∧\n    ∃ h3 : 2 * j.val - i ∈ Set.Icc 1 m,\n    color i = color j ∧ color i = color ⟨2 * j - i, h3⟩\n\nabbrev all_colorings_are_good (m : ℕ) : Prop :=\n  3 ≤ m ∧ ∀ color : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2, coloring_is_good color\n\nlemma lemma1 {m n : ℕ} (hmn : m ≤ n) (hm : all_colorings_are_good m) :\n    all_colorings_are_good n := by\n  constructor\n  · exact hm.1.trans hmn\n  · intro c\n    let c' : Set.Icc 1 m → Fin 2 :=\n      fun x ↦ c ⟨x.val, by rw [Set.mem_Icc]; exact ⟨x.prop.1, x.prop.2.trans hmn⟩⟩\n    obtain ⟨⟨i, hi1, hi2⟩, ⟨j, hj1, h